descript.abstract:
This dataset displays the main cities of Indonesia. It is a subset of the Gridded Population of the World (GPW), Global Rural-Urban Mapping Project (GRUMP), Alpha version of version 1: settlement points. This data also provides with population counts of the settlements points for 2000, 1995, 1990. The World Resources Institute prepared this dataset for use in the Interactive Atlas of Indonesia's Forests (2009).
The original GRUMP data was produced by the Socioeconomic Applications and Data Center (SEDAC) of CIESIN at Columbia University. The original data are available from the SEDAC website.
descript.supplinf:
This is the alpha release of version 1 of the GRUMP product. See the GPW home page for additional information on the product: http://sedac.ciesin.columbia.edu/gpw
If you should discover any problems or errors, please inform us at: gpw@ciesin.columbia.edu
The Global Rural-Urban Mapping Project (GRUMP), Alpha Version consists of estimates of human population for the years 1990, 1995, and 2000 by 30 arc-second (1km) grid cells and associated datasets dated circa 2000. The data products include population count grids (raw counts), population density grids (per square km), land area grids (actual area net of ice and water), mean geographic unit area grids, urban extents grids, centroids, a national identifier grid, national boundaries, coastlines, and settlement points. These products vary in GIS-compatible data formats and geographic extents (global, continent [Antarctica not included], and country levels). A proportional allocation gridding algorithm, utilizing more than 1,000,000 national and sub-national geographic units, is used to assign population values to grid cells. Additional global grids are created from the 30 arc-second grid at 1/4, 1/2, and 1 degree resolutions. The Spatial Reference metadata section information applies only to global extent, 30 arc-second resolution. This dataset is produced by the Columbia University Center for International Earth Science Information Network (CIESIN) in collaboration with the International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI), The World Bank, and Centro Internacional de Agricultura Tropical (CIAT).

The name of the continent in which the place is found.
United Nations Statistics Division regional name: sets of countries
The name of the country in which the settlement is found.
United Nations Statistics Division code: numeric code unique to each country
International Organization for Standardization (ISO), three-letter country, three character code unique to each country.
Unique ID: This is a numeric code unique to each settlement
Search Name: the name of the settlement with all non-alphabetic characters (including spaces) removed
Search Administrative Name: Subnational administrative unit in which the settlement lies, with all non-alphabetic characters (including spaces) removed.
Latitude: the north/south coordinate of the settlement in ± decimal degrees, no sign (+) = North; negative sign (-) = South
ongitude: the east/west coordinate of the settlement in ± decimal degrees, no sign (+) = East; negative sign (-) = West.
Type of Settlement: refers to city, town, urban agglomeration etc. "C" tends to refer to city, but can also refer to commune or communidad. UA tends to refer to urban agglomeration or urban area.
Population: the population of the settlement as documented by the most recent data sources available (census, statistical yearbook etc..)
Year: the year in which the most recent population data was found (referring to the POP field data)
Urban or Rural Settlement: designates whether a settlement is urban (u) or rural (r) based on country or continent specific criteria for the size of urban settlements.
1990 Population Estimate: An estimate of the settlement population in 1990 calculated intrinsically from a time series of population data or based on UN growth rates and most recent population data.
1995 Population Estimate: An estimate of the settlement population in 1995 calculated intrinsically from a time series of population data or based on UN growth rates and most recent population data.
2000 Population Estimate: An estimate of the settlement population in 2000 calculated intrinsically from a time series of population data or based on UN growth rates and most recent population data.
Population Source: the source of the population data in the POP field.
Type of Source: the type of source in which the population data was found (Census, provisional census, estimate etc.).
Location of Data Source: where the data was found. (website, where possible, or the location of the hard copy
Coordinate Source: The name of the source from which the latitude and longitude coordinates for the place were found.
